<br />
Aggression<br />
While you have the initiative, each Dwarf is damage +1.<br />
Fellowship: Spot a dwarf who is damage +X to draw X cards.  Discard this condition.<br />
<br />
It&#39;s from the siege of Gondor, a recent set, so it&#39;s readily available.  It&#39;s also common.  I&#39;ll repeat, it is common.  This means that you have no excuse for not playing it in your dwarf deck.  It is so powerful, that it should be uncommon at least.<br />
<br />
When I first took a look at this card, I was unimpressed.  Why would my already powerful dwarves need more damage?  Also, it cannot be counted on when you lose the initiative.  I never even considered the power of card drawing.  I was naive, thinking that reconciling my hand was all I needed.  I was wrong, dead wrong.<br />
<br />
Let&#39;s take a look at the first part.  Each dwarf is damage +1 while you have the initiative.  This in itself is not bad at all.  With multiple copies of aggression out, your dwarves can easily become damage +2 or higher.  It helps that Aggression costs only 1, further hurting your opponent.  This combos well with honed, which makes a dwarf who is damage +X strength +X.  Honed is free, which makes it even better.  Probably the best use for the damage +1 is with alternate ring-bearer gimli.  While he is damage +X, he is resistance +X.  These alternate ring bearers need all the help they can get resistance wise.<br />
<br />
The second part of the card is completely broken.  I was in a game against my friend with only Gimli at site 8.  Gimli was damage +7 with a variety of cards and 2 Aggressions out.  I sac one of the Aggressions, draw 7 cards, play the aggression I just drew, sac that one, draw 7 more cards, sac my last aggression and draw 6 more cards.  I had just drawn almost half of my entire deck in one turn!  Needless to say, I played 8 pumps and killed the two nazguls he sent out (A combined power of 24).  Aggression had just won me the game.  A measly common had just won the game.<br />
<br />
Summary<br />
<br />
Pros<br />
<br />
Cheap, costs only one<br />
Helps out Gimli, bearer of grudges<br />
Prevents bad draws by drawing massive amounts of cards<br />
EACH dwarf in your companionship benefits<br />
<br />
Cons<br />
Damage +1 only with initiative<br />
Susceptible to condition removal<br />
<br />
<br />
Keep in mind that this is merely an informative article.  You may already know that Aggression is good.  Yes I&#39;m stating the obvious but I&#39;m letting everyone else know how good Aggression is.  I myself didn&#39;t realize it’s potential until someone told me and I tried it out.  This card will make your deck.  I am constantly amazed at how the commons in LotR can play such an itegral part of good decks.  The webs for shelob decks are common.  Aggression is commmon.  Sam, son of Hamfast (best burden remover) is common.  That&#39;s what I love about this game.  With other games, to even consider building a good deck, you need half your deck composed up of rares.  <br />
